<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-08-04T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-08-04T22:00:00-05:00" n="438" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d438">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M)/8069: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Long</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-08-04T23:00:00-04:00">August 4,
                                    1942—11 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>562. Your 626, July 31 and 632, August 1.<note n="92" xml:id="d438fn92">Neither printed.</note> Rubber Reserve has instructed Grace and
                            Company to purchase rubber at agreement price pending conclusion of
                            arrangements with Ecuadorian Development Corporation. Reports received
                            from Grace and Company indicate rubber destined for Argentina referred
                            to in your no. 587 of July 18<note n="93" xml:id="d438fn93">Not
                                printed.</note> has been acquired for Rubber Reserve. Please
                            confirm.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>